Here is a basic example using HTML for the form and PHP for the server-side script to save the data to a text file.

You will need two files: `index.html` and `save.php`.

**1. `index.html` (The Form)**
This file creates the user-facing form with a text area and a submit button.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Text Input Form</title>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Submit Your Text</h1>

    <form action="save.php" method="post">
        <label for="user_text">Enter text below:</label><br>
        <textarea id="user_text" name="user_text" rows="10" cols="50" required></textarea>
        <br><br>
        <input type="submit" value="Save Text">
    </form>

</body>
</html>
```

**2. `save.php` (The Script to Save Data)**
This script receives the text submitted from the form and appends it to a file named `data.txt`.

```php
<?php
// Check if the form was submitted using the POST method
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    // Check if the 'user_text' field is not empty
    if (!empty($_POST['user_text'])) {

        // Get the text from the textarea
        $text_to_save = $_POST['user_text'];

        // Specify the file to save to
        $file_name = 'data.txt';

        // Add a timestamp and a separator for clarity
        $content = "--- Saved on " . date("Y-m-d H:i:s") . " ---\n" . $text_to_save . "\n\n";

        // Use file_put_contents to append the content to the file
        // FILE_APPEND flag prevents overwriting the file each time
        // LOCK_EX flag prevents other users from writing to the file at the same time
        if (file_put_contents($file_name, $content, FILE_APPEND | LOCK_EX)) {
            echo "<h1>Success</h1>";
            echo "<p>Your text has been saved successfully.</p>";
            echo "<a href='index.html'>Go back</a>";
        } else {
            echo "<h1>Error</h1>";
            echo "<p>Unable to save your text. Please check file permissions.</p>";
        }

    } else {
        echo "<h1>Error</h1>";
        echo "<p>No text was submitted. Please go back and enter some text.</p>";
    }
} else {
    // If not a POST request, redirect back to the form
    header("Location: index.html");
    exit();
}
?>
```

### How to Use:
1.  Save the two code blocks above into files named `index.html` and `save.php` respectively.
2.  Place both files in the same directory on a web server that supports PHP.
3.  Open `index.html` in your web browser.
4.  Type text into the text area and click "Save Text".
5.  The `save.php` script will run, and a new file named `data.txt` will be created in the same directory, containing your submitted text. Each new submission will be added to the end of this file.

**Note:** Ensure that your web server has permission to write files in the directory where these scripts are located.
